<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870102-0171 </DOCNO><HL> IBM Is AwardedNavy ContractsFor $377.8 Million</HL><DD> 01/02/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> IBM NOC GE RTN HON NPH SPA ML SMF LOR LSI SOSI ROKAEROSPACE (ARO)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   International Business Machines Corp. received Navy contracts totaling $377.8 million for combat systems for attack submarines.    Units of Northrop Corp. won contracts totaling $366.7 million for electronic equipment for the Air Force and missile sensors for the Army.    Units of General Electric Co. were awarded Air Force contracts totaling $246.6 million to improve Minuteman III ICBM equipment and to produce test equipment.    Units of Raytheon Co. received contracts totaling $107 million for Patriot missile support and training services for the Army and training equipment for the Navy.    Honeywell Inc. was awarded a $67.1 million Army contract for anti-tank missiles.    Units of Rockwell International Corp. received contracts totaling $52.3 million for aircraft radio parts for the Navy and aircraft testing for the Air Force.    Magnavox Government andamp; Industrial Electronics Co., a unit of North American Philips Corp., got Navy contracts totaling $47.1 million for sonobuoys. Sparton Corp. received Navy contracts totaling $46 million for sonobuoys.    Units of Martin Marietta Corp. received Air Force contracts totaling $38.3 million for spare parts for aircraft navigation equipment and space-launch vehicle software services.    Johns Hopkins University won a $33.8 million Navy contract for scientific research.    Singer Co. received contracts totaling $27.9 million for training equipment for the Navy and to maintain helicopter simulators for the Army.    Loral Corp. won a $21.9 million Air Force contract for radar warning receivers for aircraft.    Sippican Ocean Systems Inc. was awarded Navy contracts totaling $18.8 million for sonobuoys and underwater transmitters.    Lear Siegler Inc. got an $18.5 million Air Force contract for navigation equipment for C-130 aircraft.    Lukens Steel Co. received a $17.3 million Army contract for armor plate.    Life Cycle Engineering Inc. received a $12.6 million Navy contract for maintenance of ship equipment. </TEXT></DOC>